fields.name: globalStepDown
fields.doc: The step down function's delta size when adjusting the drop rate. Should be between 0.0 - 1.0. Defaults to 0.2.

fields.name: globalStepUp
fields.doc: The step up function's delta size when adjusting the drop rate. Should be between 0.0 - 1.0. Defaults to 0.2.

fields.name: initialRecoveryLevel
fields.doc: When a node is completely degraded, this config is used to determine the starting recovery weight for that node. Should be between 0.0 - 1.0. Defaults to 0.01.

fields.name: ringRampFactor
fields.doc: How fast should load balancer ramp up node that has been 100% degraded and is being recovered. This is used with initialRecoveryLevel to recover the traffic of a node. Defaults to 1.0.

fields.name: highWaterMark
fields.doc: If average ms latency for the entire service is over this number then we consider the service is in a bad state. Defaults to 3000ms.

fields.name: lowWaterMark
fields.doc: If average ms latency for the entire service is lower than this number then we consider the service is in a good state. Defaults to 500ms.

fields.name: pointsPerWeight
fields.doc: The number of points per weight given for a particular node in a hash ring. Defaults to 100.

fields.name: updateIntervalMs
fields.doc: Interval in ms between each round of load balancer calculation. Defaults to 5000ms.

fields.name: minCallCountHighWaterMark
fields.doc: If call count for the cluster for this service is over this number then we can use the statistics to calculate drop rate. Defaults to 10.

fields.name: minCallCountLowWaterMark
fields.doc: If call count for the cluster for this service is below this number then we will not use the statistics to calculate drop rate. Defaults to 5.

fields.name: hashMethod
fields.doc: What hashing method used to hash incoming request. Used to determine which node should serve the request. Choices are Random, UriRegex

fields.name: hashConfig
fields.doc: Configuration used to supplement the hash method.

fields.name: updateOnlyAtInterval
fields.doc: Whether to update load balancer strategy state only at each update interval.

fields.name: hashRingPointCleanupRate
fields.doc: The highest ratio of unused entries over the total entries of the Ring points that d2 maintains.

fields.name: consistentHashAlgorithm
fields.doc: Consistent hash algorithm the d2 load balancer should use. Defaults to POINT_BASED.

fields.name: numberOfProbes
fields.doc: The number of probes used to look up a key in consistent hash ring. Defaults to 21.

fields.name: numberOfPointsPerHost
fields.doc: The number of points on MultiProbe hash ring for each host. Defaults to 1.

fields.name: boundedLoadBalancingFactor
fields.doc: The balancing factor that enables the bounded-load feature, which is a decorator of consistent hashing algorithms. No single server is allowed to have a load more than this factor times the average load among all servers. A value of -1 disables the feature. Otherwise, it is a factor greater than 1. Defaults to -1.

fields.name: errorStatusRegex
fields.doc: Regular expression to match the status code indicates a server-side error.

fields.name: lowEmittingInterval
fields.doc: Low emitting interval (in ms) for D2Monitor events. Generally used when abnormal events present in D2Monitor that need higher emitting frequency.

fields.name: highEmittingInterval
fields.doc: High emitting interval (in ms) for D2Monitor events. Used for normal D2Monitor Event emitting.

fields.name: name
fields.doc: The name of this degrader.

fields.name: logEnabled
fields.doc: Whether degrader-specific logging is enabled or not. Defaults to false.

fields.name: maxDropRate
fields.doc: The maximum drop rate that this degrader can achieve. Values are from 0.0 - 1.0. Defaults to 1.0.

fields.name: upStep
fields.doc: Degrader's step function's delta size for increasing the drop rate. Values are from 0.0 - 1.0. Defaults to 0.2.

fields.name: downStep
fields.doc: Degrader's step function's delta size for decreasing the drop rate. Values are from 0.0 - 1.0. Defaults to 0.2.

fields.name: minCallCount
fields.doc: The minimum number of call count that should be achieved before degrader start using the call statistics to compute drop rate. Defaults to 10.

fields.name: highLatency
fields.doc: If the call latency during the interval exceeds this value, then we will increase the drop rate by upStep. Defaults to 3000ms.

fields.name: lowLatency
fields.doc: If the call latency during the interval is under this value, then we will decrease the drop rate by downStep. Defaults to 500ms.

fields.name: highErrorRate
fields.doc: If the error rate during the interval exceeds this value, then we will increase the drop rate by upStep. Values are from 0.0 - 1.0. Defaults to 1.1.

fields.name: lowErrorRate
fields.doc: If the error rate during the interval is under this value, then we will decrease the drop rate by downStep. Values are from 0.0 - 1.0. Defaults to 1.1.

fields.name: highOutstanding
fields.doc: If the latency of outstanding calls during the interval exceeds this value, then we will increase the drop rate by upStep. Defaults to 10000ms.

fields.name: lowOutstanding
fields.doc: If the latency of outstanding calls during the interval is under this value, then we will decrease the drop rate by downStep. Defaults to 500ms.

fields.name: minOutstandingCount
fields.doc: If the number of minOutstanding calls exceeds this value then we will consider outstanding latency to compute drop rate. Defaults to 5.

fields.name: maxDropDuration
fields.doc: maximum duration that is allowed when all requests are dropped. For example, if maxDropDuration is 1 min and the last request that should not be dropped is older than 1 min, then the next request should not be dropped. Defaults to 60000ms.

fields.name: latencyToUse
fields.doc: latency used to calculate the drop rate. Defaults to AVERAGE.

fields.name: initialDropRate
fields.doc: The initial drop rate that this degrader should start with. Defaults to 0.0. For values greater than 0, it means the tracker client corresponding to this degrader will receive less than 100% of the normal traffic initially and slowly recover from there.

fields.name: slowStartThreshold
fields.doc: The drop rate threshold that controls whether the degrader should perform slow start(by doubling the transmission rate) or the normal stepUp/Down operation. Defaults to 0.0 which means no slow start phase will be performed.

fields.name: logThreshold
fields.doc: The computed drop rate threshold to log degrader state changes. The log is enabled only when current drop rate higher than or equal to the threshold value.

fields.name: preemptiveRequestTimeoutRate
fields.doc: Preemptively timeout requests at a fraction of the configured request timeout after entering a degraded state. A value of 0.8 indicates 20% preemptive application of request timeout. Defaults to 1.0.

record.name: D2DegraderProperties
record.doc: Degrader properties that is applied to all tracker clients talking to this particular D2 service

symbolToDoc.RELATIVE_TRAFFIC:
This strategy aims to maintain a proportional amount of incoming QPS at the host level between the source and dark clusters.
Configured with "multiplier". For example a multiplier of 1 would mean the average incoming QPS for a source host equals that
of a dark host. A multiplier of 2 means on average a dark host will receive 2x more traffic than a source host.
symbolToDoc.CONSTANT_QPS: This strategy will try to maintain a certain queries per second to the entire dark cluster. Configured with "dispatcherOutboundTargetRate".
symbolToDoc.IDENTICAL_TRAFFIC:
This strategy aims to send identical traffic across all the dark clusters configured with this strategy. For eg: if
there are 3 dark clusters configured with this strategy with a multiplier of 1, all 3 dark clusters would receive
exactly same requests from the source clusters. This strategy can be used in scenarios where users want to do performance
analysis across dark clusters in which case having exactly similar traffic coming into all the clusters would help
make a fair comparison

enum.name: DarkClusterStrategyName
enum.doc:
There are 2 types of strategy: RELATIVE_TRAFFIC, CONSTANT_QPS. These can be specified in prioritized order and
will be picked in that order depending on availability.
A strategy may not be available when a new strategy is introduced but the client has not upgraded to a code version
that supports that strategy.

fields.doc: A timestamp corresponding to the creation of this resource/association/sub-resource

fields.name: lastModified
fields.doc: A timestamp corresponding to the last modification of this resource/association/sub-resource. If no modification has happened since creation, lastModified should be the same as created

fields.name: deleted
fields.doc: A timestamp corresponding to the deletion of this resource/association/sub-resource. Logically, deleted MUST have a later timestamp than creation. It may or may not have the same time as lastModified depending upon the resource/association/sub-resource semantics.

record.name: D2ChangeTimeStamps
record.doc: Data captured on a resource/association/sub-resource level giving insight into when that resource/association/sub-resource moved into various lifecycle stages, and who acted to move it into those lifecycle stages.

fields.name: upStep
fields.doc: Step function delta size for increasing a server's health score. Values are from 0.0 - 1.0.

fields.name: downStep
fields.doc: Step function delta size for decreasing a server's health score. Values are from 0.0 - 1.0.

fields.name: relativeLatencyHighThresholdFactor
fields.doc:
A server whose latency is above this specified factor of the cluster average is considered unhealthy,
and its health score will be decreased by downStep.
Values must be greater than both 1.0 and relativeLatencyLowThresholdFactor.

fields.name: relativeLatencyLowThresholdFactor
fields.doc:
A server whose latency is below this specified factor of the cluster average is considered healthy,
and its health score will be increased by upStep.
Values must be greater than 1.0 and below relativeLatencyHighThresholdFactor.

fields.name: highErrorRate
fields.doc:
If the error rate during the interval exceeds this value, then we will decrease the health score by downStep.
Values are from 0.0 - 1.0.

fields.name: lowErrorRate
fields.doc:
If the error rate during the interval is under this value, then we will increase the health score by upStep.
Values are from 0.0 - 1.0.

fields.name: minCallCount
fields.doc:
The health score for a server will not be calculated unless the number of calls to it in the interval
meets or exceeds the minimum call count.

fields.name: updateIntervalMs
fields.doc: The interval (in milliseconds) between each round of health score calculations.

fields.name: initialHealthScore
fields.doc:
The initial health score that a server starts with.
Values are from 0.0 - 1.0.

fields.name: slowStartThreshold
fields.doc:
The health score threshold that determines whether D2 should perform slow start
(by doubling the health score) or the normal stepUp/Down operation.
Values are from 0.0 - 1.0. A value of 0.0 means slow start is disabled.

fields.name: errorStatusFilter
fields.doc: A request status code that falls within any of the provided ranges will be considered as a server-side error.

fields.name: emittingIntervalMs
fields.doc: Emitting interval (in milliseconds) for D2Events.

fields.name: enableFastRecovery
fields.doc:
When enabled, fully degraded hosts will "recover" health despite not taking any traffic.
The health recovery will model that of slow start. Health score will be doubled as long
as the number of requests toward the entire cluster exceed the minimum call count (minCallCount).
The idea is to prevent unhealthy hosts from never receiving traffic and being able to
naturally recover due to their health score and overall QPS to the cluster being too low.

fields.name: quarantineProperties
fields.doc: Quarantine properties.

fields.name: ringProperties
fields.doc: Ring properties.

record.name: D2RelativeStrategyProperties
record.doc:
Relative load balancer strategy properties for a particular D2 service.

Balances traffic to hosts within a service by dynamically adjusting a server's health score
based on call statitics compared relatively to the performance of the entire cluster.

Health score is rated on a scale from 0.0 - 1.0, with 0.0 meaning most unhealthy (all traffic
routed away) and 1.0 meaning most healthy (no traffic routed away). Note that this behavior is
inverse of dropRate in the degrader strategy.

fields.name: URI
fields.doc: URI for this machine.

fields.name: clusterName
fields.doc: The cluster where this URI belongs.

fields.name: partitionDescription
fields.doc: partitionId key to weight

record.name: D2Uri
record.doc: A URI resource as represented in D2

fields.name: queryPostThreshold
fields.doc: The minimum size of GET requests parameters before we start converting it to POST request.

fields.name: requestTimeout
fields.doc: Timeout in ms for this transport client. Defaults to 10s.

fields.name: streamingTimeout
fields.doc: Streaming Timeout in ms for this transport client. Disabled by default (-1)

fields.name: maxResponseSize
fields.doc: Max payload that this transport client can carry in bytes. Defaults to 2MB.

fields.name: maxHeaderSize
fields.doc: Maximum size, in bytes, of all headers for a single HTTP request/response. Defaults to 8KB.

fields.name: maxChunkSize
fields.doc: Maximum chunk size, in bytes, of HTTP chunked encoding. Defaults to 8KB.

fields.name: poolSize
fields.doc: Maximum size of the underlying HTTP connection pool. Defaults to 200.

fields.name: poolWaiterSize
fields.doc: Maximum waiters waiting on the HTTP connection pool.

fields.name: poolStatsNamePrefix
fields.doc: Custom prefix of the name of the pool stats.

fields.name: tcpNoDelay
fields.doc: Flag to enable/disable Nagle's algorithm. Defaults to true

fields.name: poolStrategy
fields.doc: The strategy HTTP connection pool uses to select connections. Defaults to MRU.

fields.name: minPoolSize
fields.doc: Minimum size of the HTTP connection pool

fields.name: maxConcurrentConnections
fields.doc: Maximum connection requests this transport client can send to an endpoint concurrently.

fields.name: idleTimeout
fields.doc: interval after which idle connections will be automatically closed. Defaults to 25s.

fields.name: sslIdleTimeout
fields.doc: interval after which idle SSL connections will be automatically closed. Defaults to 2h 55m.

fields.name: shutdownTimeout
fields.doc: timeout, in ms, the client should wait after shutdown is initiated before terminating outstanding requests. Defaults to 5s

fields.name: gracefulShutdownTimeout
fields.doc: timeout, in ms, the client should wait for exiting http2 streams before shutting down the connection. Defaults to 30s

fields.name: responseCompressionOperations
fields.doc: operations where compression should be used

fields.name: responseContentEncodings
fields.doc: preferred content encodings for responses, used to construct Accept-Encoding header

fields.name: requestContentEncodings
fields.doc: supported content encodings for requests

fields.name: useResponseCompression
fields.doc: whether to enable response compression or not

fields.name: allowedClientOverrideKeys
fields.doc: a list of keys in D2TransportClientProperties which client can override

fields.name: protocolVersion
fields.doc: service desired transport client protocol version e.g. HTTP/1.1, HTTP/2

fields.name: maxClientRequestRetryRatio
fields.doc:
Service desired maximum ratio of retry requests to total requests per client. The retry ratio is applied
only when D2 RetryClient is enabled.

record.name: D2TransportClientProperties
record.doc: The properties that is applied when creating transport client to talk to this particular D2 service

symbolToDoc.POINT_BASED: Point-based consistent hash ring. The more points the ring has, the more balanced it is.
symbolToDoc.MULTI_PROBE: Multi-probe consistent hash. The more probes to use, the more balanced the ring is.
symbolToDoc.DISTRIBUTION_BASED: Use points of hosts to build a distribution and make randomized host selection. NOTE: this algorithm DOES NOT support sticky routing

fields.name: quarantineMaxPercent
fields.doc:
The max percentage of hosts in the cluster that can be quarantined at the same time.
Values are from 0.0 - 1.0. A value of 0.0 means quarantine is disabled.

fields.name: healthCheckMethod
fields.doc: The http method used for health checking quarantined hosts. Defaults to OPTIONS method.

fields.name: healthCheckPath
fields.doc: The path used for health checking quarantined hosts. eg: "/<contextPath>/admin". Defaults to the service path.

record.name: D2QuarantineProperties
record.doc:
Properties for D2 quarantine.

Severely unhealthy hosts can be placed in quarantine, in which "dummy" requests with a
customizable method/path are used as pings to check endpoint health instead of real requests.

fields.name: pointsPerWeight
fields.doc: The number of points per weight given for a particular node in a hash ring. Defaults to 100.

fields.name: hashMethod
fields.doc: What hashing method used to hash incoming request. Used to determine which node should serve the request. Choices are Random, UriRegex

fields.name: hashConfig
fields.doc: Configuration used to supplement the hash method.

fields.name: hashRingPointCleanupRate
fields.doc: The highest ratio of unused entries over the total entries of the Ring points that d2 maintains.

fields.name: consistentHashAlgorithm
fields.doc: Consistent hash algorithm the d2 load balancer should use. Defaults to POINT_BASED.

fields.name: numberOfProbes
fields.doc: The number of probes used to look up a key in consistent hash ring. Defaults to 21.

fields.name: numberOfPointsPerHost
fields.doc: The number of points on MultiProbe hash ring for each host. Defaults to 1.

fields.name: boundedLoadBalancingFactor
fields.doc: The balancing factor that enables the bounded-load feature, which is a decorator of consistent hashing algorithms. No single server is allowed to have a load more than this factor times the average load among all servers. A value of -1 disables the feature. Otherwise, it is a factor greater than 1. Defaults to -1.

record.name: D2RingProperties
record.doc: D2 hash ring properties used for load balancing.

fields.name: cost
fields.doc: Maximum number of backup requests expressed in percent. For example, value 5 means that clients will not make more than 5% of additional backup requests. The actual number of backup requests is not guaranteed and this strategy allows for short bursts of additional requests in order to be effective. Minimum value is 1 and maximum value is 99.

fields.name: historyLength
fields.doc: Decision on when to make a backup requests is based on recent history of response times. This property specifies how many recent requests should be taken into consideration. Minimum value is 100.

fields.name: requiredHistoryLength
fields.doc: Decision on when to make a backup requests is based on recent history of response times. This property specifies how many requests are needed in order to start making backup requests. Minimum value is 100.

fields.name: maxBurst
fields.doc: It is expected that backup requests will happen in bursts e.g. when one of the hosts is experiencing long GC pause. Capping number of backup requests in a continuous way would decrease effectiveness of this technique in common case. This property specifies the maximum size of backup requests burst. For example, value 64 means that there might be 64 consecutive backup requests made even though it means that this burst temporarily exceeds specified percentage limit. See documentation of BurstyBarrier class for detailed discussion. Minimum value is 1.

fields.name: minBackupDelayMs
fields.doc: Backup request may be made after certain delay that is dynamically calculated based on recent response times. This parameter is a minimum value for that delay. This parameter may help limit number of backup requests if SLA is already met. For example, if this parameter has value 5, then no backup requests will be made if max response time is lower than 5ms. 0 means that there is no minimum backup delay. Value must not be negative.

record.name: BoundedCostBackupRequests
record.doc: Configuration of bounded cost backup requests strategy. This strategy attempts to keep cost (number of backup requests expressed in percents) of backup requests close to specified limit. This strategy will try not to make more backup requests than specified. The actual number of backup requests is not guaranteed and allows for short bursts of additional requests in order to be effective.
